merset, England"},"en":{"1410–1457":"1410–1457","1410–1475":"1410–1475","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1450–1504":"1450–1504","1452–1514":"1452–1514","1456–Male":"1456–Deceased","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","1514":"1514","1457":"1457","1456":"1456","1445":"1445","1410":"1410","1475":"1475","1452":"1452","1496":"1496","about 1445":"about 1445","about 1456":"about 1456","about 1442":"about 1442","about 1452":"about 1452","about 1450":"about 1450","1504":"1504","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Westminster, Middlesex, England":"Westminster, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","Wedmore, Somerset, England":"Wedmore, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Raynes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (West Yorkshire): variant of   Raines  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Raines","meanings":["English: variant of   Raine  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: habitational name from Rayne (Essex), recorded in the Domesday Book as <i>Raines</i> in the 11th century. The etymology of the placename is uncertain, but it may derive from Old English <i>hrægene</i> ‘hut, shelter’ or from a pre-English river name for Pods Brook (a river on which Rayne lies), cognate with the German river name Regen (a tributary of the Danube), formed from the Indo-European root <i>reg-</i> ‘wet, moisten, water’.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Rennes in Brittany, France."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Raynes was born in 1410, in Westminster, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom, her father, William Raynes, was 30 and her mother, Raynes, was 30. She married Thomas Mede about 1442, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1457, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1410–1457":"1410–1457","1410–1475":"1410–1475","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1450–1504":"1450–1504","1452–1514":"1452–1514","1456–Male":"1456–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","1514":"1514","1457":"1457","1456":"1456","1445":"1445","1410":"1410","1475":"1475","1452":"1452","1496":"1496","about 1445":"umbes 1445","about 1456":"umbes 1456","about 1442":"umbes 1442","about 1452":"umbes 1452","about 1450":"umbes 1450","1504":"1504","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Westminster, Middlesex, England":"Westminster, Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wedmore, Somerset, England":"Wedmore, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"1410–1457":"1410–1457","1410–1475":"1410–1475","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1450–1504":"1450–1504","1452–1514":"1452–1514","1456–Male":"1456–Kuollut","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1450":"1450","1380":"1380","1514":"1514","1457":"1457","1456":"1456","1445":"1445","1410":"1410","1475":"1475","1452":"1452","1496":"1496","about 1445":"noin 1445","about 1456":"noin 1456","about 1442":"noin 1442","about 1452":"noin 1452","about 1450":"noin 1450","1504":"1504","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Westminster,